│ and used outside (in the preheader of loop.2 after we restructure),           │
│ preservation of LCSSA (PreserveLCSSA flag) requires introducing an LCSSA PHI  │
│ for %load. The pass performs several CFG splits (SplitBlock /                 │
│ SplitBlockPredecessors) before and after SCEV expansion. The PHI %load.lcssa  │
│ ends up created after SCEV has already expanded the trip count using the      │
│ original value placeholder and later replaced with the LCSSA PHI, causing the │
│ use (%0 = shl i64 %load.lcssa, 3) to reside in a block not dominated by the   │
│ PHI's block.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nIn UnrollRuntimeLoopRemainder        │
│ (LoopUnrollRuntime.cpp) the code splits the loop preheader (lines ~705–735    │
│ for epilog remainder case) and then immediately expands TripCount and BECount │
│ SCEVs at the old preheader's terminator (lines ~760–770) before ensuring      │
│ outer-loop defined values used in those expansions are in proper LCSSA form   │
│ relative to the transformed CFG. Subsequent CFG updates (additional splits    │
│ for exit blocks or remainder loop construction) invoke utilities that may     │
│ insert LCSSA PHIs (e.g., SplitBlockPredecessors with suffix .unr-lcssa /      │
│ .epilog-lcssa) after expansion. The SCEVExpander rewrites uses to the newly   │
│ created PHI, but because that PHI is now in a successor block (e.g.,          │
│ NewPreHeader) while the earlier arithmetic (%0 = shl ...) remains in the      │
│ original preheader, dominance is broken. The pass assumes the loop is already │
│ in LCSSA form (only guaranteed for the loop being unrolled, not for values    │
│ coming from an enclosing loop). It neglects to proactively form LCSSA for any │
│ outer-loop values that SCEV will reference before CFG restructuring. Thus the │
│ ordering—expansion first, LCSSA repair later—creates a use before the         │
│ definition dominates.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Points(s):\nFile:                   │
