│ produced earlier in the same transformation.                                  │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ SCEV reports trip count for loop.2 as ((8 + (8 * %load)) /u 8) which          │
│ simplifies to %load + 1. The expansion necessarily reuses the value loaded in │
│ the outer loop (%load) after control transfers from loop.1 to loop.2. Because │
│ %load is defined in loop.1 and used outside (in the preheader of loop.2 after │
│ we restructure), preservation of LCSSA (PreserveLCSSA flag) requires          │
│ introducing an LCSSA PHI for %load. The pass performs several CFG splits      │
│ (SplitBlock / SplitBlockPredecessors) before and after SCEV expansion. The    │
│ PHI %load.lcssa ends up created after SCEV has already expanded the trip      │
│ count using the original value placeholder and later replaced with the LCSSA  │
│ PHI, causing the use (%0 = shl i64 %load.lcssa, 3) to reside in a block not   │
│ dominated by the PHI's block.                                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In UnrollRuntimeLoopRemainder (LoopUnrollRuntime.cpp) the code splits the     │
│ loop preheader (lines ~705–735 for epilog remainder case) and then            │
│ immediately expands TripCount and BECount SCEVs at the old preheader's        │
│ terminator (lines ~760–770) before ensuring outer-loop defined values used in │
│ those expansions are in proper LCSSA form relative to the transformed CFG.    │
│ Subsequent CFG updates (additional splits for exit blocks or remainder loop   │
│ construction) invoke utilities that may insert LCSSA PHIs (e.g.,              │
│ SplitBlockPredecessors with suffix .unr-lcssa / .epilog-lcssa) after          │
│ expansion. The SCEVExpander rewrites uses to the newly created PHI, but       │
│ because that PHI is now in a successor block (e.g., NewPreHeader) while the   │
│ earlier arithmetic (%0 = shl ...) remains in the original preheader,          │
│ dominance is broken. The pass assumes the loop is already in LCSSA form (only │
│ guaranteed for the loop being unrolled, not for values coming from an         │
│ enclosing loop). It neglects to proactively form LCSSA for any outer-loop     │
│ values that SCEV will reference before CFG restructuring. Thus the            │
│ ordering—expansion first, LCSSA repair later—creates a use before the         │
│ definition dominates.                                                         │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Points(s):                                                   │
│ File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopUnrollRuntime.cpp, lines 760–770 (just    │
│ before expanding TripCount/BECount).                                          │
│ Edit: Insert a call to ensure LCSSA for values from outer loops needed by     │
│ SCEV prior to expansion. Specifically, if PreserveLCSSA is true, invoke       │
│ formLCSSARecursively on the loop being unrolled to bring all required outer   │
│ loop values into LCSSA before any SCEV expansions that will use them. This    │
│ guarantees any PHIs inserted dominate subsequent instructions, preventing the │
│ dominance violation.                                                          │
│ Concrete patch concept (pseudocode insertion before TripCount expansion):     │
│ if (PreserveLCSSA && DT && LI) {                                              │
│   // Ensure outer loop values used in trip count expansion are already in     │
│ LCSSA.                                                                        │
│   formLCSSARecursively(*L, *DT, *LI, SE);                                     │
│ }                                                                             │
│ This uses existing utility to convert required values from containing loops   │
│ into proper LCSSA form before we introduce new preheader splits and SCEV      │
│ expansions.                                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ Rationale: By forming LCSSA prior to expansion, SCEVExpander will directly    │
│ reference the correct dominating PHI (%load.lcssa placed in the original exit │
│ block) and no later CFG split will move that definition below its uses. The   │
│ dominance relation will hold, removing verifier failure.                      │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The crash stems from improper ordering in UnrollRuntimeLoopRemainder: SCEV    │
│ expansion of trip count uses a value from an outer loop before establishing   │
│ its LCSSA PHI in a dominating block, leading to a dominance violation after   │
│ CFG modifications create the PHI later. Adding a pre-expansion LCSSA          │
│ formation call (formLCSSARecursively) at lines 760–770 ensures all required   │
│ outer-loop values are in LCSSA prior to expansion, maintaining dominance and  │
│ fixing the verifier failure without altering profitability heuristics or      │
│ other logic.                                                                  │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
